Rose Ejembi, Makurdi A lecturer with the Benue State University, Dr. Stephen Akuma, has purchased his nomination and intent forms to contest the 2019 governorship election in Benue State. Akuma, who is contesting on the platform of the National Conscience Party (NCP), said he is in the race to change the narrative of retrogression and underdevelopment in Benue State. Said he, “Since the return of democracy in 1999, Benue has witnessed retrogression and development had been in the negative progression. And that is why I decided to come in and liberate the state. READ ALSO: I’m in the race to change the narrative of Benue – APC guber hopeful “We had good governance between 1979 and 1983 led by Aper Aku and then Adasu came in thereafter. The administration of these two governors witnessed massive development in Benue and I want to follow in their footsteps. “I am hoping that if given the opportunity to govern Benue State, history will remember me as one of the best governors in the state,” Akuma stated. Speaking on the peoples’ response to his candidature during his consultations so far, Dr. Akuma maintained that the Benue people have embraced him with open arms sighting a scenario where market women willingly donated their widows mites to aid his movement in Agatu and Katsina-Ala, respectively. He expressed optimism that the Benue electorate would elect him so as to change the narrative respecting the leadership jinx that had hitherto been experienced in the state.